      "text": "The Case of Two Scientific Networks: Rival Positions"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "fa4a2b552ce7766f",
      "text": "Different portions of the heritage left by Leibnitz, were taken hold of by the two traditions (A) and (B), which emerged from the cybernetic foundations laid in the 1940s."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "60cffe35ef2b872c",
      "text": "His ideas about computation and artificial language came to be pursued within tradition (A), defining itself as concerned with [[Artificial Intelligence]] (AI)."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "1222d9e2b52a3efa",
      "text": "In terms of this position, Plato's [[Steersman]] may be seen as a regulator, operating through the use of symbolic representations, in spite of their limiting rationality (Cf. H. Simon). A good regulator of a system requires a [[Model]] of that system, although one must take care to distinguish between relevant levels (Cf. A. Newell)."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "2a789c2fbd1e3bfb",
      "text": "Leibnitz' theory of self-contained monads, each living in a closed universe, with no windows to the outside, may be recognized in the principles of [[Autopoiesis]] (of cellular self-creative production) as advanced by the other tradition (B)."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "b051610cbd71a2bb",
      "text": "The cybernetic notion of circular loops is retained, but stripped of external reference and mapping relations. The term \"in-formation\" is only reluctantly used in the sense of forming from within."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "8189503a62e75894",
      "text": "[[Regulation]], if having sense at all, would have to involve the relations of production of some order, maintaining the presence of participants in a continuous self-creative circle."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "b90c0c9f870cba69",
      "text": "Consistent with these different perspectives, cognitive interaction came to be viewed differently:"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "d5b120aa4c7b5ed6",
      "text": "(A) In the first tradition, declared by H. Simon to belong to the sciences of the artificial, symbolic representations are considered basic, and human and computer intelligence are viewed as employing roughly \"the same symbol-manipulating processes\". Computer simulation of cognitive processes is seen as one of the few investigative means to study such complex processes."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "3a109ab41d61c0ff",
      "text": "(B) In the other tradition, H. Maturana argues that \"magic words as … symbolization\" serve only to conceal the autopoietic phenomena of cognition and linguistic interaction. Systems operating in and by themselves (auto) need to be distinguished from those made for and by others (allo), and require additional operational explanations."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "fff5055ddafbf2fc",
      "text": "There has thus been a reductionistic tendency in both positions: For (A) in the Artificial Gestalt of computer representation, for (B) in the Biological Gestalt of cellular reproduction."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "4f3fe8475a8c457c",
      "text": "However, qua networks of cognitive interaction among scholars, each of the two rival traditions (A) and (B), has exhibited behavioral modes that conform to principles of the rival one."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "db5ccdb1d94e55b2",
      "text": "In the first tradition (A), the network soon disengaged itself from other cybernetic traditions, defining its domain as that of AI in a self-enclosing manner. This fits the principle of organizational closure, postulated in the rival tradition."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "c8e8b4f10232a505",
      "text": "In the latter tradition (B), symbolic representations in an allopoietic system were resorted to in order to demonstrate [[Autopoiesis]]. This use of computer simulation is quite consistent within the rival tradition."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "a67ac77a1a7cbbb9",
      "text": "Thus, at least in the context of scientific communities themselves, behavioral modes conforming to both the Artificial Gestalt of (A) and to the Biological Gestalt of (B), can be shown to exist in each of the systems concerned."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "216388e85be79d09",
      "text": "This, in turn, is one of the concerns of a third position (D), the Dialogical Gestalt of conversation and complementarities, which should not be confused with a metaposition."
    },
